  <section class="prog-section ba-section" id="before-after">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Before &amp; After</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">The same question, before and after the SHARP Method</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__sub">What changes when a student picks the right method instead of guessing. (Illustrative example &mdash; a typical trigonometry question, not a real student script.)</p>

      <div class="ba-question">
        <span class="ba-q-label">Trigonometry &middot; Non-right-angled triangle &middot; 3 marks</span>
        <p>In triangle ABC, AB = 8&nbsp;cm, AC = 6&nbsp;cm and angle BAC = 50&deg;. Find the length of BC.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ba-grid">
        <div class="ba-card ba-card--before">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--before">Before</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">Uses SOH-CAH-TOA: &ldquo;cos&nbsp;50&deg; = BC / 8&rdquo; &rarr; BC = 5.14&nbsp;cm.</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li>Assumed a right angle that isn&rsquo;t there</li>
            <li>Wrong tool &mdash; SOH-CAH-TOA only works for right-angled triangles</li>
            <li>No valid method, so no method marks</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--before">Typically 0 / 3</span>
        </div>

        <div class="ba-card ba-card--after">
          <span class="ba-tag ba-tag--after">After SHARP</span>
          <p class="ba-answer">Right-angle check &rarr; not right-angled; two sides + included angle &rarr; <strong>cosine rule</strong>: BC&sup2; = 8&sup2; + 6&sup2; &minus; 2(8)(6)cos&nbsp;50&deg; &rarr; BC &asymp; 6.19&nbsp;cm.</p>
          <ul class="ba-notes">
            <li><strong>Right-angle check</strong> first &mdash; the RULE framework</li>
            <li>Correct tool: two sides &amp; the included angle &rarr; cosine rule</li>
            <li>Full working shown &mdash; every method mark earned</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="ba-mark ba-mark--after">3 / 3</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="ba-footnote">Illustrative teaching example, not a real student script. Choosing the method with a right-angle check is the <strong>RULE</strong> framework we drill at the <strong>Hit</strong> step of the SHARP Method.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== INSIDE A LESSON ===== -->
  <section class="prog-section lesson-flow" id="lesson-flow">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inside a Lesson</p>
      <h2 class="prog-section__heading">What 90 minutes at A-Worthy actually looks like</h2>
      <p class="prog-section__intro">Most parents have never seen the inside of a maths tuition lesson. Here&rsquo;s exactly how a typical O-Level Mathematics session unfolds &mdash; from the first warm-up question to the homework that gets set before students log off.</p>

      <ol class="lesson-timeline">
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">01</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">0 &ndash; 5 min &middot; Retrieval warm-up</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Five questions, ninety seconds each</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Five quick-fire questions on last week&rsquo;s techniques &mdash; a factorisation, an angle calculation, a ratio problem, a graph sketch, a probability question. Students answer in the chat or on their whiteboards. Anyone who fumbles gets a one-line reminder before we move on. Retrieval is the most underrated study habit, so we build it into every session.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">02</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">5 &ndash; 15 min &middot; Question of the week</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Read the question before you solve</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">We project a real past-paper question on screen and walk through the <em>See</em> step together. What command word is being used? How many marks is it worth &mdash; and what does that tell us about the expected method? Which framework will we reach for? By minute fifteen, every student knows exactly what method to use before they write a single line of working.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">03</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">15 &ndash; 30 min &middot; Framework walkthrough</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Name the tool, then use the tool</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">READ, LABEL, PLOT, DATA, RULE, SHOW &mdash; whichever framework matches the day&rsquo;s focus. Jeremy demonstrates with a model solution, then deliberately writes a flawed version so students can spot the error. Naming the tool means students can reach for it again on exam day without the tutor in the room.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">04</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">30 &ndash; 60 min &middot; Live problem-solving &amp; feedback</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Three feedback touches per student</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students attempt the question on screen-shared whiteboards or documents. Jeremy moves between solutions in real time, flagging issues as they happen &mdash; missing geometric reasons, sign errors in algebra, incorrect formula selection in trigonometry. This is where the small class size matters: every student gets at least three feedback touches in thirty minutes.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">05</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">60 &ndash; 75 min &middot; Peer checking</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">Train the examiner&rsquo;s eye</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">Students swap solutions and check each other&rsquo;s working against the official Cambridge mark scheme. Checking trains the examiner&rsquo;s eye &mdash; the moment a student sees what loses marks in someone else&rsquo;s working, they stop making the same mistake in their own.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="lesson-step">
          <span class="lesson-step__num" aria-hidden="true">06</span>
          <div class="lesson-step__body">
            <span class="lesson-step__time">75 &ndash; 90 min &middot; Exit ticket</span>
            <h3 class="lesson-step__title">No busywork goes home</h3>
            <p class="lesson-step__desc">A two-question exit ticket confirms what stuck. Jeremy sets one focused practice piece &mdash; usually fifteen minutes of work &mdash; with a worked solution dropped on WhatsApp the next morning. No busywork. Every assignment maps to a specific weakness identified in that session.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="lesson-flow__note">Sessions run weekly on the A-Worthy Whiteboard with every lesson recorded, so any student who misses a week can catch up before the next one.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

